<H1><CENTER>The Nobel Prize in Chemistry 1912</CENTER>
</H1>
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="chemistry-medalj.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM" width=93 height=93><BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>
<H3><CENTER>&quot;for the discovery of the so-called Grignard reagent, which
in recent years has greatly advanced the progress of organic chemistry&quot;</CENTER>
</H3>
<BR><CENTER><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=5> <TR ALIGN=CENTER> <TD NOWRAP>
<IMG SRC="chemistry-1912-1.gif" WIDTH="140" HEIGHT="198" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR>
<BR>
<B>Victor Grignard</B><BR>
<BR>
France<BR>
<BR>
Nancy University<BR>
Nancy, France<BR>
<BR>
1871 - 1935<BR>
<BR>
</TD> </TR> </TABLE><BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>
<H3><CENTER>&quot;for his method of hydrogenating organic compounds in the
presence of finely disintegrated metals whereby the progress of organic
chemistry has been greatly advanced in recent years&quot;</CENTER>
</H3>
<P><CENTER><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=5> <TR ALIGN=CENTER> <TD NOWRAP><IMG SRC=
"chemistry-1912-2.gif" WIDTH="140" HEIGHT="198" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"> <BR>
<BR>
<B>Paul Sabatier</B><BR>
<BR>
France<BR>
<BR>
Toulouse University,<BR>
Toulouse, France<BR>
<BR>
1854 - 1941<BR>
<P></TD> </TR> </TABLE> <BR>
