<html>
<head>
 <title>Database of Laureates - Instructions</title>
</head>

<body>

<CENTER><h2>Database of Laureates - Instructions</h2></CENTER>

<strong>Prize categories:</strong><br>
Mark the prize category(ies) by clicking on the square to the right of the 
prize that you are interested in. You may activate as 
many categories as you wish. Note that you have to mark at least one, otherwise
nothing will be fetched or searched. <p>

<strong>Years:</strong><br>
Specify the year you want the search to begin with and end at. 
If you leave these two fields blank, all years will be searched. 
If you leave the "begin" field blank, the search will begin from 1901. If 
you leave the "end year" field blank, the search will continue until the last 
entry. <p>

If you leave the rest of the form (the search part) blank, you will get a list 
of all Laureates in the prize categories during the years that you have 
specified. If you mark all the prize categories and leave the year fields blank 
you will get information about all Laureates in the database.<p>

For a more detailed search fill in the rest of the form according to your own 
wish. Note 
that the search will only be made among the documents specified by the fields 
above.<p>

<strong>Searching by names:</strong><br>
You may search for a specific Laureate by using field 1. The following should
be considered:
<li>The search is case insensitive. 

<li>If you specify several names,
separated by spaces, only entries containing all names will be matched.

<li>If the name contains local characters, you should
specify them using 8 bit ISO code. If you can not use this, simply substitute all
characters that you are uncertain of with a dot character. In other words, if 
you want to search for "BJRNSON", you may search for "Bj.rnson". 
<li>If you need even more complicated search patterns, you may use "extended regular expressions"
as in "egrep".
<p>

<strong>Searching by country, city or university:</strong><br>
You may search for a Laureate's home or birth country and city or 
the university the laureate is/was working at, by using field 2.<br>
The same considerations as for the "name" field should be applied.
<p>

<strong>Searching by keywords:</strong><br>
You may search for keywords in the motivations by using field 3.<br>
The same considerations as for the "name" field should be applied.
<p>

<strong>Searching for the year of birth or death of a Laureate:</strong><br>
You may search for the year of birth field 4, or death field 5 of a Laureate.
<p>

Note: If you fill in several of the fields, only those entries that match
all your criteria will be listed. In other words, currently only "and" searches 
and not "or" searches may be done.<p>
<HR><CENTER><BR>
