<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Ascani Sobrero</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BR>
<HR>
<CENTER><H1>Ascanio Sobrero</H1>
(1812-1888)<HR>
<BR>
<BR><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="sobrero.gif"></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
Italian chemist who discovered nitroglycerine. 
Ascanio worked
as an assistant to Professor Pelouse in Paris and then became professor
of chemistry in Turino, Italy. His face was badly scarred as a result of
an explosion in the 1840s. He considered nitroglycerine to be far too dangerous
to be of any practical use. Sobrero is quoted to have said &quot;When I
think of all the victims killed during nitroglycerine explosions, and the
terrible havoc that has been wreaked, which in all probability will continue
to occur in the future, I am almost ashamed to admit to be its discoverer.&quot;
He was mortified when the Nobel family started the commercial exploitation
of nitroglycerine and with the success of dynamite he felt he had been subject
to an injustice. Alfred Nobel openly cited Sobrero as the inventor of nitroglycerine.
<HR><CENTER><BR>
