<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Poster3</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>

<FONT SIZE=2>
During his first period in Russia, Immanuel Nobel designed explosive mines for the Russian War Ministry.  In this watercolor painted by himself, he shows how to lay pyrotechnic mines in ports and narrow waterways.<BR><BR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="mines.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=239>
</CENTER>

<TABLE><TR><TD><FONT SIZE=2>
The brothers Alfred, left, and Ludvig in St. Petersburg, probably in the late 1840s.  Under the guidance of their father, practical work at the Russian factory, known as the Nobel & Sons Iron Foundry and Mechanical Workshop (Fonderies & Ateliers M&eacute;caniques Nobel & Fils) was part of their education.
</TD><TD>
<IMG SRC="brothers.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=101>
</TD></TR></TABLE><BR>

<CENTER>

<H1>St. Petersburg</H1>


<P><P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
"I am a misanthrope, but exceedingly benevolent;  I am very cranky, and am a super- idealist [ ... ], <BR>
I can digest philosophy better than food."
</CENTER>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2></CENTER>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Alfred Nobel (1894)<P><BR>

<P>

<CENTER><TABLE CELLSPACING=5><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD WIDTH=33%>


<FONT SIZE=5>T<FONT SIZE=3>he Nobel family was reunited in 1842 in Russia.  Immanuel had succeeded in interesting the War Ministry in his designs for land and sea mines, and his company prospered very soon.<P>


	Alfred and his brothers were educated by Russian tutors, 
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%>

who<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>provided a broad education.  It was during these years in St. Petersburg that Alfred's quest for knowledge  asserted itself.  At the age of 17, he spoke five languages: Swedish, Russian, English,  French and German.  His father sent him out into the world 
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%>
on<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>educational travels.  
Alfred went to Europe and to the United States.  These travels lasted for two years and had an important impact on his future.


</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER>

