<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Poster4</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<CENTER>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<FONT SIZE=2>
Photograph of Alfred Nobel, probably dating from his return to Russia.  Precocious and unusually intelligent, he was a dreamer and a loner.  His long trip abroad led him to open up to the outside world and become more outgoing.
</TD><TD>
<IMG SRC="alfred-sobrero.gif" WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=170>
</TD><TD>
<FONT SIZE=2>
In Professor Pelouze's laboratory, Nobel learned how to produce nitroglycerine.  Several chemists had followed in Sobrero's footsteps, but it was Alfred Nobel who first saw the practical applications of this liquid.
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<H1>Alfred Nobel, the traveler</H1>


<P><P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
"How pitiful to want to be someone or something in the motley crowd of 1.4 billion two-legged, tailless apes running around on our revolving earth projectile."<P>
<FONT SIZE=2></CENTER>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Alfred Nobel<P><BR>

<P>

<CENTER><TABLE CELLSPACING=5><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD WIDTH=33%>

<FONT SIZE=5>I<FONT SIZE=3>n the course of his educational travels, Alfred went to Paris, where he studied with the famous scientist Professor T.J. Pelouze.  It was in the Pelouze laboratory that he first came into contact with nitroglycerine, an extremely explosive liquid (glyceryl trinitrate) 
  </TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%>
that<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>was first discovered in 1846 by the Italian Ascanio Sobrero, one of Professor Pelouze's earlier students.

Alfred Nobel saw the potential offered by a product like this.  When he was back in St. Petersburg he tried to find a solution to how to achieve a controlled explosion using nitroglycerine.
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%>
Alfred<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>Nobel had a passion for literature.  During one of his visits in Paris he wrote a long poem in 419 lines in English: "You say I am a riddle ..." a declaration of love to a young, beautiful Parisian girl:

</TD></TR></TABLE>

<TABLE WIDTH=80%><TR><TD>
<IMG SRC="poem.gif" WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=173>
</TD><TD VALIGN=TOP>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
"You say I am a riddle - it may be,<BR>
For all of us are riddles unexplained.<BR>
Begun in pain, in deeper torture ended<BR>
This breathing clay what business has it here?<BR>
Some petty wants to chain us to the earth,<BR>
Some lofty thoughts to lift us to the spheres<BR>
...
</TD></TR></TABLE>
</CENTER>

<HR><P>
<CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=75%><TR><TD WIDTH=33% HALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="poster3.html">[PREVIOUS POSTER]</A>
