Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Poster6</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<CENTER>


<H1>Paris</H1>

<FONT SIZE=4>
"My factories may perhaps put an end to war sooner than your congresses. The day when two army corps will be able to destroy each other in one second, all civilised nations will recoil from war in horror and disband their armies."
      <P>
<FONT SIZE=2></CENTER>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Alfred Nobel to Bertha von Suttner (1892)<P><BR><BR>

<CENTER>

<TABLE WIDTH=500><TR>
<TD WIDTH=150 VALIGN=BOTTOM>
<FONT SIZE=2>Nobel's house at 59, Avenue Malakoff (today Avenue Raymond Poincar&eacute;).  Despite the fact that he was forbidden to continue his research in Paris - his favourite city - he kept this house until his death.
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=200 VALIGN=BOTTOM>
<FONT SIZE=2>Among other things the house had an impressive winter garden that Nobel used as a dining room.
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=150 VALIGN=BOTTOM>
<FONT SIZE=2>Nobel's private mansion was demolished in 1910 and replaced by a house in the "Art Nouveau" style (Architect: Charles Letrosne; Interior decorator: Camille Garnier).  Today it houses the Alain Ducasse restaurant (earlier Jo&euml;l Robuchon). <BR>
<FONT SIZE=1>Photo: P. Weerbook.
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<IMG SRC="paris.gif" WIDTH="500" HEIGHT="376">

<TABLE WIDTH=500><TR>
</TD><TD WIDTH=200>
<FONT SIZE=2>Bertha von Suttner was to play a major role in inspiring Nobel's pacifist ideas.  She became famous for the novel "Lay Down Arms!".  She was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1905.

</TD><TD WIDTH=300>
<FONT SIZE=2>The laboratory in Sevran where Nobel invented smokeless powder was situated near the powder magazines of the French government.  This gave birth to accusations that Nobel was guilty of espionage, and later - after he had offered the Italian government the right to manufacture ballistite - of "high treason."
</TD></TR></TABLE>

</CENTER>

<BR><BR>

<P>

<CENTER><TABLE CELLSPACING=5><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD WIDTH=33%>

<FONT SIZE=5>I<FONT SIZE=3>n 1873 Alfred Nobel settled in Paris, his favourite city.  There he found a sophistication that, according to him, had nothing to do with social class: "Even the dogs reek with civilization, here in Paris."  He bought a magnificant house in Avenue Malakoff, not far from the Bois de Boulogne.
	Although he was wealthy, he was above all a lonely man, who had dedicated his life to science research and travels all around the world.  
  </TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%>
In<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>the spring of 1876 he ran an advertisement to find a secretary.  This is how he met Countess Bertha Kinsky von Chinic und Tettau, then 33 years old, who later became a famous pacifist writer under the name of Bertha von Suttner.
	Bertha worked with him for a very short time, but they remained lifelong friends.  Bertha's ideas had a strong influence on Alfred and contributed to his ideas to create a peace prize.
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%>

	Shortly<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>afterwards, Alfred Nobel met the young and beautiful Sofie Hess in Austria.  Their complicated and sometimes touching relationship lasted for 18 years.
	Forced by circumstances - he was accused of "high treason against France" and thus had to close his laboratory in Sevran - Nobel, disappointed and bitter, left the French capital in 1891 and settled in San Remo, Italy, where he died, alone, on December 10, 1896.

</TD></TR></TABLE>

</CENTER>

<HR><P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE WIDTH=75%><TR><TD WIDTH=33% HALIGN=CENTER>
