<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Poster7</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE><TR><TD>
<FONT SIZE=2>* On Victor Hugo's 83rd birthday, February 22, 1885, Nobel sent a telegram to "the Master, "
with hopes for a long life so that he could continue to "enchant the world and propagate his great ideas about universal love of mankind."
</TD><TD>
<IMG SRC="hugo.gif" WIDTH="300" HEIGHT="101">
</TD></TR></TABLE>


<H1>Alfred Nobel and literature</H1>

<FONT SIZE=4>
"A recluse without books and ink is a dead man before he dies."
      <P>
<FONT SIZE=2></CENTER>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Alfred Nobel<P><BR>


<CENTER><TABLE CELLSPACING=15><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD WIDTH=300>

<FONT SIZE=5>T<FONT SIZE=3>o remedy his feelings of loneliness during his youth in St. Petersburg, Alfred Nobel read and wrote incessantly, a habit that continued all his life.  If his real home was his work, books and writing came second.  At his death, he left behind an extensive private correspondence and a library of more than a thousand books: by Shakespeare, Voltaire and the best French, English, German, Russian and Scandinavian writers of the 20th century.  Bertha von Suttner was a witness to this; during her first visit at Avenue Malakoff she was impressed by a library that was so "well furnished, capable of satisfying the most varied tastes."<P>

Inspired by Shelley and Byron,  at an early age Nobel chose to write poems in English.  He detested Zola and the naturalist movement, but on the other hand he loved Hugo (whom he knew personally)*, Balzac, Maupassant, Turgenev and the works of Norway's Bj&oslash;rnson (Nobel Prize in Literature in 1903), essentially devoted to the idea of progress.  He also appreciated Herbert Spencer, whose philosophy to a great extent corresponded with his own ideas.<P>

Alfred Nobel, apparently fascinated by language, always searched for conciseness.  His literary gift was perhaps the aphorism, which is not without a certain self-critical sense of humour as well as having an ironic tone.  He was the author of a tragedy, Nemesis, a horror story inspired by the criminal life of the Cencis, which was printed some weeks after his death in a hundred copies of which all but three were destroyed by order of the family.  Finally, for a long time Nobel worked on a social novel that remained unfinished, Monsieur Avenir, which put forward his political ideas.

</TD><TD WIDTH=150>
<BR><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>
Every now and then Nobel was invited to Hugo in Avenue d'Eylau, the same street where Afred had rented an appartment for young Sofie Hess.<P>
Victor Hugo at the French Academy, caricatured by M&eacute;rim&eacute;e.
<P>

<IMG SRC="hugo-drawing.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=136>

</TD></TR></TABLE>

</CENTER>

<HR><P>
<CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=75%><TR><TD WIDTH=33% HALIGN=CENTER>
