<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Poster10</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<CENTER>


<H1>The beginning of the century </H1>
<H2>"a lofty and sound idealism"</H2>


<TABLE CELLSPACING=5><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD WIDTH=33%>
<FONT SIZE=3>
During the first decade, the Nobel Prize in Literature was understood to be not just a literary award; the literary quality of a work was weighed against its contribution to "humanity's struggle toward the ideal." The will was interpreted in the light of the conservative idealism and the idealist aesthetics of the 19th century:  the Laureate's works
<BR><BR><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="prudhomme.gif" WIDTH="150" HEIGHT="200"><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>
SULLY PRUDHOMME <BR>(*1839 Paris - &#134;1907 Ch&acirc;tenay)<BR>
- "in special recognition of his poetic composition, which gives evidence of lofty idealism, artistic perfection and a rare combination of the qualities of both heart and intellect."</CENTER>

</TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%><FONT SIZE=3>
 ought to be of  "a lofty and sound idealism," characterized by "a true nobility not simply of presentation but of conception and of philosophy of life." which in fact excluded both naturalism and symbolism.  

In 1901, the final candidates, among twenty-five nominees, were the two Frenchmen Sully Prudhomme and Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Mistral.  The Swedish Academy found it proper to take into account the heavy support expressed for Sully Prudhomme by numerous members of the French Academy; the Swedish Academy reasoned that with "such a weighty recommendation," the award should be greeted with justified assent.  It was not: World opinion protested against the neglect of Tolstoy.  How could such a nomination be rejected?  

</TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%>
<FONT SIZE=3>
The Nobel Committee recognized, of course, the master of War and Peace, but had decisive objections on matters of principle: 
"in countless of his works he denies not only the church, but the state, even the right of property - which he himself, inconsistently, enjoys - and contests the right of individuals and peoples to self-defense."<BR><BR>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="mistral.gif" WIDTH="150" HEIGHT="200"><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>
FR&Eacute;D&Eacute;RIC MISTRAL <BR>(*1830 Maillane, Bouches du Rh&ocirc;ne - &#134;1914)<BR>
- "in recognition of the fresh originality and true inspiration of his poetic production, which faithfully reflects the natural scenery and native spirit of his people, and, in addition, his significant work as a Proven&ccedil;al philologist." 
</CENTER>   
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<BR>

None of the early Laureates met the requirement of a "lofty and sound idealism" so well as Kipling, whose idealism, according to the Committee reports,  also contained "a primitive, almost myth-making strength of imagination."<P>

1901 Ren&eacute; Sully Prudhomme, France<BR>
1902 Theodor Mommsen, Germany<BR>
1903 Bj&oslash;rnstierne Bj&oslash;rnson, Norway<BR>
1904 Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Mistral, France and   Jos&eacute; Echegaray, Spain<BR>
1905 Henryk Sienkiewicz, Poland<BR>
1906 Giosu&egrave; Carducci, Italy<BR>
1907 Rudyard Kipling, Great Britain (born in British India)<BR>
1908 Rudolf Eucken, Germany<BR>
1909 Selma Lagerl&ouml;f, Sweden<BR>
1910 Paul Heyse, Germany<BR>
<P>

</CENTER>

<HR><P>
<CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=75%><TR><TD WIDTH=33% HALIGN=CENTER>
