<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Poster11</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<CENTER>


<H1>World War I </H1>
<H2>"literary neutralism"</H2>

 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=5><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD WIDTH=33%>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="maeterlinck.gif" WIDTH="150" HEIGHT="200"><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>
MAURICE MAETERLINCK <BR>(*1862 Gand - &#134;1949 Nice)<BR>
- "in appreciation of his many-sided literary activities, and especially of his dramatic works, which are distinguished by a wealth of imagination and by a poetic fancy, which reveals, sometimes in the guise of a fairy tale, a deep inspiration, while in a mysterious way they appeal to the readers' own feelings and stimulate their imaginations."
</CENTER>

</TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%><FONT SIZE=3><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="rolland.gif" WIDTH="150" HEIGHT="200"><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>
ROMAIN ROLLAND <BR>(*1866 Clamecy, Ni&egrave;vre - &#134;1944)<BR>
- "as a tribute to the lofty idealism of his literary production and to the sympathy and love of truth with which he has described different types of human beings." - By this choice, the Academy wanted to award an author whose significance was more than national, a pacifist whose fiction included both Germany and France without committing itself to either.
</CENTER>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="tagore.gif" WIDTH="150" HEIGHT="200"><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>
RABINDRANATH TAGORE <BR>(*1861 Calcutta - &#134;1941)<BR>
- "because of his profoundly sensitive, fresh and beautiful verse, by which, with comsummate skill, he has made his poetic thought, expressed in his own English words, a part of the literature of the West." - The Prize was greeted with enthusiasm in India, and the consequence of this has been that since then India has kept sending the Academy new proposals.
</CENTER>
</TD></TR>



<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD WIDTH=33%>
<FONT SIZE=5>T<FONT SIZE=3>he next period of the Nobel Prize in Literature began with a careful reorientation.  In 1913 the Swedish Academy abandoned its European orientation by selecting the Indian writer Tagore.  In an individual memo, one member of the Academy expressed a point of view that was unusual for its time and would not play a leading role in the Nobel 
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%>
discussion<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>until six decades later: "For the first time ...
we would have the chance to discover a great name before it had already spent years haunting the newspaper columns."  The outbreak of World War I, however, halted all such outward-reaching initiatives.  The new dominant ideology could be called "literary neutralism."  The Committee had found that
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%>
 Nobel's<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>purpose was above all to prevent any kind of nationalist partiality.  
The neutrality policy favoured smaller nations outside the belligerent groups and gave the Scandinavian literatures a special chance.  The heavy representation of Scandinavia in the list of winners can be partly explained by the neutrality policy of the World War I years.

</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>
1911 Maurice Maeterlinck, Belgium<BR>
1912 Gerhart Hauptmann, Germany<BR>
1913 Rabindranath Tagore, India<BR>
1914 -<BR>
1915 Romain Rolland, France<BR>
1916 Verner von Heidenstam, Sweden<BR>
1917 Karl Gjellerup, Denmark and 
         Henrik Pontoppidan, Denmark<BR>
1918 -<BR>
1919 Carl Spitteler, Switzerland<BR>


<P>

</CENTER>

<HR><P>
<CENTER><TABLE WIDTH=75%><TR><TD WIDTH=33% HALIGN=CENTER>
