<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Poster13</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<CENTER>


<H1>The 1930s </H1>
<H2>a literature of  "universal interest"</H2>

<TABLE CELLSPACING=5><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD WIDTH=33%>
<FONT SIZE=5>T<FONT SIZE=3>he Nobel Prize was intended for those who "shall have conferred the greatest benefit on mankind." In stressing the "universal" aim of the Prize, the Academy of the 1930s excluded de facto the whole of 
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%>
modern<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>poetry with its demanding complexity and restricted appeal, dismissing it as "obscure, esoteric and difficult" (i.e. Paul Val&eacute;ry).  The prizewinners of this decade admittedly include innovators like Luigi 
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%>
Pirandello<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>and Eugene O'Neill, but more striking, certainly, were the prizes to Sinclair Lewis, John Galsworthy and Pearl Buck, authors who could all speak to a "wider general public."
</TD></TR></TABLE>

 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=5><TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="bounine.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>
IVAN BUNIN<BR>(*1870 Voronez, Russia - &#134;1953 Paris)<BR>
- for the strict artistry with which he has carried on the classical Russian traditions in prose writing. - The citation had various implications; on the one hand it gave belated recognition to a great tradition whose foremost representative, Tolstoy, had been passed over by the Academy. On the other hand it implied that Bunin satisfied the general accessibility criterion.  Bunin had emigrated to France in 1920 and had settled in Paris.</CENTER>

</TD><TD VALIGN=BOTTOM><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>
LUIGI PIRANDELLO<BR>(*1867 Girgenti, Sicilie - &#134;1936 Rome)<BR>
- for his bold and ingenious revival of dramatic and scenic art.  In the choices of Pirandello (1934) and O'Neill (1936) we can see omens of the radically different judgments that were to be made after World War II.<BR><BR>
<IMG SRC="pirandello.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140></CENTER><BR>

</TD><TD VALIGN=TOP><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="oneill.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>
EUGENE O'NEILL<BR>(*1888 New York - &#134;1953 Boston)<BR>
- for the power, honesty and deep-felt emotions of his dramatic works, which embody an original concept of tragedy.  In O'Neill's plays, the Academy recognized the "poetic strength" anticipating his position in what has been called "The Age of O'Neill" in American theater.</CENTER><BR>


</TD><TD VALIGN=BOTTOM><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>

ROGER MARTIN DU GARD<BR>(*1881 Neuilly - &#134;1958 Bell&ecirc;me, Orne)<BR>
- for the artistic power and truth with which he has depicted human conflict as well as some fundamental aspects of contemporary life in his novel-cycle "Les Thibault." The Permanent Secretary of the Academy, Anders &Ouml;sterling, emphasized that the work of Martin du Gard "hardly has any equivalent in the contemporary production as far as vitality, universality of its significance and psychological richness."<BR><BR>
<IMG SRC="dugard.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140><BR></CENTER>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<BR>





<P>
1930 Sinclair Lewis, United States<BR>
1931 Erik Axel Karlfeldt, Sweden<BR>
1932 John Galsworthy, Great Britain<BR>
1933 Ivan Bunin, stateless domicile in France (born in Russia)<BR>
1934 Luigi Pirandello, Italy<BR>
1935 -<BR>
1936 Eugene O'Neill, United States<BR>
1937 Roger Martin du Gard, France<BR>
1938 Pearl Buck, United States<BR>
1939 Frans Eemil Sillanp&auml;&auml;, Finland<BR>
1940-43 -<BR>
1944 Johannes V. Jensen, Denmark<BR>
1945 Gabriela Mistral, Chile<BR>


<P>

</CENTER>

