<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Poster14</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<CENTER>


<H1>The post-war period - "the innovators"</H1>

 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=5><TR>
<TD WIDTH=33%><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="gide.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=2>
ANDR&Eacute; GIDE<BR>(*1869 Paris - &#134;1951)<BR>
- for his comprehensive and artistically significant writings, in which human problems and conditions have been presented with a fearless love of truth and keen psychological insight. <P>

<IMG SRC="hemingway.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=2>

ERNEST HEMINGWAY<BR>(*1899 Oak Park, Illinois - &#134;1961 Ketchum, Idaho)<BR>
- for his mastery of the art of narrative, most recently demonstrated in "The Old Man and the Sea," and for the influence that he has exerted on contemporary style. 


</CENTER><BR>
</TD><TD  WIDTH=33%><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>

<IMG SRC="eliot.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=200><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=2>

T.S. ELIOT<BR>(*1888 St. Louis, Missouri - &#134;1965 London)<BR>
- for his outstanding, pioneer contribution to present-day poetry. The apostrophe to the author of "The Waste Land" was also an apostrophe, by implication, to all of the great adherents of the symbolist-modernist tradition, which stretched from Mallarm&eacute; into recent times.  In his speech the Permanent Secretary also drew attention to the work of one of the most regrettable omissions, the work of James Joyce: "a work, which had a still more sensational effect on modern literature."<P>



</CENTER><BR>
</TD><TD WIDTH=33%><CENTER>

<IMG SRC="mauriac.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=2>
FRAN&Ccedil;OIS MAURIAC<BR>(*1885 Bordeaux - &#134;1970 Paris)<BR>
- for the deep spiritual insight and the artistic intensity with which he has in his novels penetrated the drama of human life.<P>

<IMG SRC="camus.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=2>
ALBERT CAMUS<BR>(* 1913 Mondovi, Algeria - &#134;1960 Villeblevin, Yonne)<BR>
- for his important literary production, which with clearsighted earnestness illuminates the problems of the human conscience in our times.  <P>





</CENTER><BR>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<BR>





<TABLE CELLSPACING=5><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD WIDTH=33%>
<FONT SIZE=5>T<FONT SIZE=3>he postwar series of prizewinners shows a radical break with the prewar record.  It is the age of the great innovators.  The key term "pioneer" is associated above all with Anders &Ouml;sterling, Permanent Secretary of </TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%>
the<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>Academy from 1941 to 1964 and chairman of the Nobel Committee from 1947 to 1970.  His stamp is clearly visible in the new policy.  The series began with Hesse (1946), Gide (1947), Eliot (1948), 
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=33%>
and<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>Faulkner (1949).  The watershed can be discerned in 1945.  That year's laureate was to be Paul Val&eacute;ry - but he died in July.
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=10><TR><TD><CENTER>
1946 Hermann Hesse, Switzerland (born in Germany)<BR>
1947 Andr&eacute; Gide, France<BR>
1948 Thomas Stearns Eliot, Great Britain<BR>
1949 William Faulkner, United States<BR>
1950 Bertrand Russell, Great Britain<BR>
1951 P&auml;r Lagerkvist, Sweden<BR>
1952 Fran&ccedil;ois Mauriac, France<BR>
</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>
1953 Winston Churchill, Great Britain<BR>
1954 Ernest Hemingway, United States<BR>
1955 Halld&oacute;r Kiljan Laxness, Iceland<BR>
1956 Juan Ram&oacute;n Jim&eacute;nez, Spain<BR>
1957 Albert Camus, France<BR>
1958 Boris Pasternak, USSR<BR>
1959 Salvatore Quasimodo, Italy<BR>
</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE>


<P>

</CENTER>

