<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Poster15</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<CENTER>


<H1>1960 - 1969</H1>

 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=5><TR>
<TD><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="sartre.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=2>
JEAN-PAUL SARTRE <BR>(*1905 Paris - &#134;1980)<BR>
- "for his work which, rich in ideas and filled with the spirit of freedom and the quest for truth, has exerted a farreaching influence in our age."<BR>
<FONT SIZE=1>Photo: L&ouml;tfi &Ouml;zk&ouml;k
 <P>

</CENTER><BR>
</TD><TD><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>

<TABLE><TR><TD>

<IMG SRC="sartre-letter.gif" WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=285><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=2>
</TD><TD VALIGN=TOP><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>
Sartre's letter of refusal:<BR>
October 14, 1964<P>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

A. &Ouml;sterling, Permanent Secretary of the Swedish Academy, Stockholm, December 10, 1964:
"The Laureate has informed us that he does not wish to receive this Prize, but the fact that he has declined the distinction of course does not at all alter the validity of the awarding."
<P>

</CENTER><BR>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<CENTER>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=20><TR><TD><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="beckett.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=200><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>
SAMUEL BECKETT <BR>(*1906 Dublin - &#134;1989 Paris)<BR>
- "for his writing, which - in new forms for the novel and drama - in the destitution of modern man acquires its elevation." - The choice of this writer shows, both a new liberal interpretation of the "idealist" requirement, and the attempt to distinguish the "life-giving force, nevertheless, in Beckett's pessimism" ... "From that position, in the realms of annihilation, rises the writing of Samuel Beckett like a miserere from all mankind, its muffled minor key sounding liberation to the oppressed and comfort to those in need."<P>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="perse.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=200><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>
SAINT-JOHN PERSE<BR> (*1887 Guadaloupe - &#134;1975 Giens, Var)<BR>
- "for the soaring flight and the evocative imagery of his poetry which in a visionary fashion reflects the conditions of our time." - Saint-John Perse was a test of the sensibilities of the Academy.  Certainly, he was "one of modern poetry's foremost pioneers," but still too obscure and complicated for the senior members.  It was a younger generation in the Academy - especially Dag Hammarskj&ouml;ld in this case - that now carried on the search for an innovator.<P></CENTER>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
</CENTER>


<P>
1960 Saint-John Perse, France<BR>
1961 Ivo Andric, Yugoslavia<BR>
1962 John Steinbeck, United States<BR>
1963 Giorgos Seferis, Greece<BR>
1964 Jean-Paul Sartre, France (declined the Prize)<BR>
1965 Mikhail Sholokhov, USSR<BR>
1966 Shmuel Yosef Agnon, Israel and
         Nelly Sachs, Sweden (born in Germany)<BR>
1967 Miguel Angel Asturias, Guatemala<BR>
1968 Yasunari Kawabata, Japan<BR>
1969 Samuel Beckett, Ireland<BR>


<P>

</CENTER>

