<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Poster16</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<CENTER>


<TABLE>

<TR><TD COLSPAN=3>
<CENTER><H1>The last decades - "a pragmatic attitude"</H1></CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=33% VALIGN=TOP>
<FONT SIZE=5>I<FONT SIZE=3>n the 1970s the Nobel Committee's promotion of the great innovators had to be reconciled with another aim: making judgments based on a "pragmatic" interpretation of Nobel's will.  The true purpose of the 
</TD><TD WIDTH=33% VALIGN=TOP>
prize,<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>it was said, was to "direct attention to an oeuvre or a literary  genre that has not been sufficiently regarded."  A breakthrough for this policy can be seen in the surprising choice in 1978 of Isaac Bashevis 
</TD><TD WIDTH=33% VALIGN=TOP>
Singer,<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>a writer not widely known.  This choice and the three following - Elytis, Milosz and Canetti - constitute a pattern that in its way was as surprising as the launching of the "pioneers" between 1946 and 1950.<P>

</TD></TR>

<TR><TD COLSPAN=3>
<CENTER><H1>"The literature of the whole world"</H1></CENTER>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=33% VALIGN=TOP>
<FONT SIZE=5>I<FONT SIZE=3>n the 1980s and 1990s we notice an ambition by the Academy to extend the area of scrutiny to new literary regions, a desire to cover 
</TD><TD WIDTH=33% VALIGN=TOP>
"the<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>literature of the whole world:" 
Gabriel Garc&igrave;a M&aacute;rquez (Colombia), Octavio Paz (Mexico), Wole Soyinka (Nigeria), Naguib Mahfouz (Egypt), 
</TD><TD WIDTH=33% VALIGN=TOP>
Nadine<FONT SIZE=5> <FONT SIZE=3>Gordimer (South Africa), 
Derek Walcott (The West Indies), Kenzaburo Oe (Japan) ... 
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>

<TABLE><TR><TD WIDTH=25% VALIGN=TOP><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="simon.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=2>
CLAUDE SIMON <BR>(*1913 Tananarive, Madagascar - Salces et Paris)<BR>
- who in his novel combines the poet's and the painter's creativeness with a deepened awareness of time in the depiction of the human condition. <P></CENTER>

</TD><TD WIDTH=25% VALIGN=TOP><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="soyinka.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=2>
WOLE SOYINKA<BR> (*1934 Abeokuta, Nigeria)<BR>
- who in a wide cultural perspective and with poetic overtones fashions the drama of existence. <P>
</CENTER>

</TD><TD WIDTH=25% VALIGN=TOP><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="mahfouz.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=2>
NAGUIB MAHFOUZ <BR>(*1911 Cairo)<BR>
- who, through works rich in nuance - now clear-sightedly realistic, now evocatively ambiguous - has formed an Arabian narrative art that applies to all mankind.<P></CENTER>

</TD><TD WIDTH=25% VALIGN=TOP><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="walcott.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140><BR><BR><FONT SIZE=2>
DEREK WALCOTT<BR>(*1930 Saint Lucia, the West Indies)<BR>
- for a poetic oeuvre of great luminosity, sustained by a historical vision, the outcome of a multicultural commitment.<P></CENTER>

</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P>
<TABLE><TR><TD><CENTER>
1970 Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn, USSR<BR>
1971 Pablo Neruda, Chile<BR>
1972 Heinrich B&ouml;ll, Federal Republic of Germany<BR>
1973 Patrick White, Australia<BR>
1974 Eyvind Johnson, Sweden and
         Harry Martinson, Sweden<BR>
1975 Eugenio Montale, Italy<BR>
1976 Saul Bellow, United States<BR>
1977 Vicente Aleixandre, Spain<BR>
